Galkovsky has an interesting bit about how colossal statues from Antiquity always have frozen expressions of indifference on their faces and rough facial features because at that large scale any facial expression or emotion looks bizarre, horrifying. Giants must look indifferent.

The indifferent face looks beautiful when looked at from afar from the street and a colossal statue with a detailed and expressive face would produce horror, but looking at an indifferent classical statue's mask-face from so close up is probably equally unnerving and captivating.

Goethe was obsessed with the Juno Ludovisi and had a giant plaster installed in his house. Goethe also had a quote about how things taken out of their natural scale like insects under a microscope appear monstrous. And in his room the Juno Ludovisi was obviously out of scale too.
